Linux File System
--------------------------
The Linux File System is the way Linux organizes, stores, and manages all files and directories on a storage device
One of the most important concepts in Linux is:
"Everything in Linux is treated as a file."

This includes:

Regular files
Directories (folders)
Hard disks
USB devices
Printers
Keyboard
Mouse
Network interfaces
Processes 

Without a file system:

The operating system would not know where files are stored.
Files could not be organized.
Programs could not read or write data.
The computer would not be able to locate the operating system itself.

The file system helps Linux:

Store files
Find files quickly
Protect files with permissions
Manage disk space
Organize data efficiently
Real-World Example

Think of a library.

The library building = Hard Disk
Shelves = Directories (Folders)
Books = Files
Librarian = Linux Kernel
Library catalog = File System
